# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-overlays
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A **data center** is a pool of resources (computational, storage, network) interconnected using a communication network.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A data center network (DCN) holds a pivotal role in a data center, as it interconnects all of the data center resources together.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] DCNs need to be scalable and efficient to connect tens or even hundreds of thousands of servers to handle the growing demands of cloud computing.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Today's data centers are constrained by the interconnection network.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The adoption of hybrid cloud computing has influenced the design of modern data center networks.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] By integrating on-premises infrastructure with private and public cloud environments, organizations can distribute applications and workloads across multiple locations.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] As a result, data center resources no longer need to be physically co-located and can communicate through interconnected network architectures.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Data center networks can be divided into multiple separate categories.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The legacy three-tier DCN architecture follows a multi-rooted tree based network topology composed of three layers of network switches, namely access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The servers in the lowest layers are connected directly to one of the edge layer switches.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The aggregate layer switches interconnect together multiple access layer switches.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] All of the aggregate layer switches are connected to each other by core layer switches.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Core layer switches are also responsible for connecting the data center to the Internet.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier is the common network architecture used in data centers.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] However, three-tier architecture is unable to handle the growing demand of cloud computing.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The higher layers of the three-tier DCN are highly oversubscribed.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, scalability is another major issue in three-tier DCN.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Major problems faced by the three-tier architecture include, scalability, fault tolerance, energy efficiency, and cross-sectional bandwidth.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier architecture uses enterprise-level network devices at the higher layers of topology that are very expensive and power hungry.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN architecture reduces the oversubscription and cross section bandwidth problem faced by the legacy three-tier DCN architecture.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN employs commodity network switches based architecture using Clos topology.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The network elements in fat tree topology also follows hierarchical organization of network switches in access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] However, the number of network switches is much larger than the three-tier DCN.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The architecture is composed of *k* pods, where each pod contains, (k/2)2 servers, k/2 access layer switches, and k/2 aggregate layer switches in the topology.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The core layers contain (k/2)2 core switches where each of the core switches is connected to one aggregate layer switch in each of the pods.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree topology can offer up to 1:1 oversubscription ratio and full bisection bandwidth, depending on each rack's total bandwidth versus the bandwidth available at the tree's highest levels.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Higher tree branches are typically oversubscribed to their lower branches by a ratio of 1:5, with the problem compounding at the highest tree levels, including up to 1:80 or 1:240, at the highest levels.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree architecture uses a customized addressing scheme and routing algorithm.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The scalability is one of the major issues in fat tree DCN architecture and maximum number of pods is equal to the number of ports in each switch.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] DCell is a server-centric hybrid DCN architecture where one server is directly connected to one server.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A server in the DCell architecture is equipped with multiple network interface cards (NICs).
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell follows a recursively built hierarchy of cells.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A cell0 is the basic unit and building block of DCell topology arranged in multiple levels, where a higher level cell contains multiple lower layer cells.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The cell0 is building block of DCell topology, which contains *n* servers and one commodity network switch.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The network switch is only used to connect the server within a cell0.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A cell1 contains *k=n+1* cell0 cells, and similarly a cell2 contains k * n + 1 dcell1.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell is a highly scalable architecture where a four level DCell with only six servers in cell0 can accommodate around 3.26 million servers.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Besides very high scalability, the DCell architecture depicts very high structural robustness.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] However, cross section bandwidth and network latency is a major issue in DCell DCN architecture.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Some of the other well-known DCNs include BCube, Camcube, FiConn, Jelly fish, and Scafida.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A qualitative discussion of different DCNs along with benefits and drawbacks associated with each one has been made available.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Scalability is one of the foremost challenges to the DCNs.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] With the advent of cloud paradigm, data centers are required to scale up to hundreds of thousands of nodes.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Besides offering immense scalability, the DCNs are also required to deliver high cross-section bandwidth.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Current DCN architectures, such as three-tier DCN offer poor cross-section bandwidth and possess very high over-subscription ratio near the root.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN architecture delivers 1:1 oversubscription ratio and high cross section bandwidth, but it suffers from low scalability limited to *k*=total number of ports in a switch.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] DCell offers immense scalability, but it delivers very poor performance under heavy network load and one-to-many traffic patterns.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] A quantitative analysis of the three-tier, fat tree, and DCell architectures for performance comparison (based on throughput and latency) is performed for different network traffic pattern.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN delivers high throughput and low latency as compared to three-tier and DCell.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] DCell suffers from very low throughput under high network load and one to many traffic patterns.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for DCell's low throughput is very high over subscription ratio on the links that interconnect the highest level cells.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell exhibits very high robustness against random and targeted attacks and retains most of its node in the giant cluster after even 10% of targeted failure. multiple failures whether targeted or random, as compared to the fat tree and three-tier DCNs.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for high robustness and connectivity of the DCell is its multiple connectivity to other nodes that is not found in fat tree or three-tier architectures.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The concerns about the energy needs and environmental impacts of data centers are intensifying.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Energy efficiency is one of the major challenges of today's information and communications technology (ICT) sector.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The networking portion of a data center is accounted to consume around 15% of overall cyber energy usage.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Around 15.6 billion kWh of energy was utilized solely by the communication infrastructure within the data centers worldwide in 2010.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] The energy consumption by the network infrastructure within a data center is expected to increase to around 50% in data centers.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] IEEE 802.3az standard has been standardized in 2011 that make use of adaptive link rate technique for energy efficiency.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, fat tree and DCell architectures use commodity network equipment that is inherently energy efficient.
[src:network-overlays/data-center-network-architectures] Workload consolidation is also used for energy efficiency by consolidating the workload on few devices to power-off or sleep the idle devices.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] In computing, **network virtualization** is the process of combining hardware and software network resources and network functionality into a single, software-based administrative entity, a **virtual network**.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Network virtualization involves platform virtualization, often combined with resource virtualization.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Network virtualization is categorized as either **external virtualization**, combining many networks or parts of networks into a virtual unit, or **internal virtualization**, providing network-like functionality to software containers on a single network server.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] In software testing, software developers use network virtualization to test software which are under development in a simulation of the network environments in which the software is intended to operate.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] As a component of application performance engineering, network virtualization enables developers to emulate connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users in a test environment without having to physically test the software on all possible hardware or system software.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] The validity of the test depends on the accuracy of the network virtualization in emulating real hardware and operating systems.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] External network virtualization combines or subdivides one or more local area networks (LANs) into virtual networks to improve a large network's or data center's efficiency.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] A virtual local area network (VLAN) and network switch comprise the key components.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Using this technology, a system administrator can configure systems physically attached to the same local network into separate virtual networks.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Conversely, an administrator can combine systems on separate local area networks (LANs) into a single VLAN spanning segments of a large network.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] External network virtualization is envisioned to be placed in the middle of the network stack and help integrating different architectures proposed for next generation networks.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Citrix and Vyatta have built a virtual network protocol stack combining Vyatta's routing, firewall, and VPN functions with Citrix's Netscaler load balancer, branch repeater wide area network (WAN) optimization, and secure sockets layer VPN.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] OpenSolaris network virtualization provides a so-called "network in a box" (see OpenSolaris Network Virtualization and Resource Control).
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Microsoft Virtual Server uses virtual machines to make a "network in a box" for x86 systems.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] These containers can run different operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows or Linux, either associated with or independent of a specific network interface controller (NIC).
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Network virtualization may be used in application development and testing to mimic real-world hardware and system software.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] In application performance engineering, network virtualization enables emulation of connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users for software testing.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Wireless network virtualization can have a very broad scope ranging from spectrum sharing, infrastructure virtualization, to air interface virtualization.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] In other words, virtualization, regardless of wired or wireless networks, can be considered as a process splitting the entire network system.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] However, the distinctive properties of the wireless environment, in terms of time-various channels, attenuation, mobility, broadcast, etc., make the problem more complicated.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Therefore, it may be inaccurate to consider wireless network virtualization as a subset of network virtualization.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Until 1 Gbit/s networks, network virtualization was not suffering from the overhead of the software layers or hypervisor layers providing the interconnects.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] With the rise of high bandwidth, 10 Gbit/s and beyond, the rates of packets exceed the capabilities of processing of the networking stacks.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] For example, in case of Openstack, network is provided by Neutron which leverages many features from the Linux kernel for networking: iptables, iproute2, L2 bridge, L3 routing or OVS.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] Since the Linux kernel cannot sustain the 10G packet rate, then some bypass technologies for a fast path are used.
[src:network-overlays/network-virtualization] The main bypass technologies are either based on a limited set of features such as Open vSwitch (OVS) with its DPDK user space implementation or based on a full feature and offload of Linux processing such as 6WIND virtual accelerator.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] An **overlay network** is a logical computer network that is layered on top of a physical network.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The concept of overlay networking is distinct from the traditional model of OSI layered networks, and almost always assumes that the underlay network is an IP network of some kind.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Some examples of overlay networking technologies are, VXLAN, BGP VPNs, and IP-over-IP technologies, such as GRE, IPSEC tunnels, or SD-WAN.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Nodes in an overlay network can be thought of as being connected by logical links, each of which corresponds to a path, perhaps through many physical links, in the underlying network.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] For example, distributed systems such as peer-to-peer networks are overlay networks because their nodes form networks over existing network connections.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The Internet was originally built as an overlay upon the telephone network, while today (through the advent of VoIP), the telephone network is increasingly turning into an overlay network built on top of the Internet.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Overlay networks have a certain set of attributes, including separation of logical addressing, security and quality of service.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Other optional attributes include resiliency, encryption and bandwidth control.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Guaranteeing bandwidth through marking traffic has multiple solutions, including IntServ and DiffServ.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] IntServ requires per-flow tracking and consequently causes scaling issues in routing platforms.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] DiffServ has been widely deployed in many operators as a method to differentiate traffic types.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] DiffServ itself provides no guarantee of throughput; it does allow the network operator to decide which traffic is higher priority, and hence will be forwarded first in congestion situations.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Overlay networks implement a much finer granularity of quality of service, allowing enterprise users to decide on an application and user or site basis which traffic should be prioritized.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Many telcos use overlay networks to provide services over their physical infrastructure.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] In the networks that connect physically diverse sites (wide area networks, WANs), one common overlay network technology is BGP VPNs.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] These VPNs are provided in the form of a service to enterprises to connect their own sites and applications.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The advantage of these kinds of overlay networks is that the telecom operator does not need to manage addressing or other enterprise-specific network attributes.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] From an enterprise point of view, while an overlay VPN service configured by the operator might fulfill their basic connectivity requirements, SD-WAN overlay networks offer additional flexibility.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The Internet is the basis for more overlaid networks that can be constructed in order to permit routing of messages to destinations not specified by an IP address.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] For example, distributed hash tables can be used to route messages to a node having a specific logical address, whose IP address is not known in advance.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Overlay networks can be incrementally deployed at end-user sites or on hosts running the overlay protocol software, without cooperation from Internet service providers.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The overlay has no control over how packets are routed in the underlying network between two overlay nodes, but it can control, for example, the sequence of overlay nodes a message traverses before reaching its destination.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The objective of resilience in telecommunications networks is to enable automated recovery during failure events in order to maintain a wanted service level or availability.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] As telecommunications networks are built in a layered fashion, resilience can be used in the physical, optical, IP or session to application layers.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Each layer relies on the resilience features of the layer below it.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Overlay IP networks in the form of SD-WAN services therefore rely on the physical, optical and underlying IP services they are transported over.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Application-layer overlays depend on all the layers below them.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The advantage of overlays is that they are more flexible and programmable than traditional network infrastructure, which can outweigh the disadvantages of additional latency, complexity and bandwidth overheads.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] The limited deployment of IP multicast, a best-effort network-layer multicast protocol, has led to considerable interest in alternate approaches that are implemented at the application layer in accordance with the end-to-end principle.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] In an overlay or end-system multicast approach, participating peers organize themselves into an overlay topology for data delivery.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] Each edge in this topology corresponds to a unicast path between two end-systems or peers in the underlying internet.
[src:network-overlays/overlay-network] All multicast-related functionality is implemented at the peers instead of at routers, and the goal of the multicast protocol is to construct and maintain an efficient overlay for data transmission.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:network-overlays/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In computer networks, a **tunneling protocol** is a communication protocol that allows for the movement of data from one network to another.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] They can, for example, allow private communications to be sent across a public network (such as the Internet), or for one network protocol to be carried over an incompatible network, through a process called encapsulation.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Because tunneling involves repackaging the traffic data into a different form, perhaps with encryption as standard, it can hide the nature of the traffic that is run through a tunnel.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling protocols work by using the data portion of a packet (the payload) to carry the packets that actually provide the service.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling uses a layered protocol model such as those of the OSI or TCP/IP protocol suite, but usually violates the layering when using the payload to carry a service not normally provided by the network.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Typically, the delivery protocol operates at an equal or higher level in the layered model than the payload protocol.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] A tunneling protocol may, for example, allow a foreign protocol to run over a network that does not support that particular protocol, such as running IPv6 over IPv4.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Another important use is to provide services that are impractical or unsafe to be offered using only the underlying network services, such as providing a corporate network address to a remote user whose physical network address is not part of the corporate network.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Users can also use tunneling to "sneak through" a firewall, using a protocol that the firewall would normally block, but "wrapped" inside a protocol that the firewall does not block, such as HTTP.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] If the firewall policy does not specifically exclude this kind of "wrapping", this trick can function to get around the intended firewall policy (or any set of interlocked firewall policies).
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Another HTTP-based tunneling method uses the HTTP CONNECT method/command.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] A client issues the HTTP CONNECT command to an HTTP proxy.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The proxy then makes a TCP connection to a particular server:port, and relays data between that server:port and the client connection.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Because this creates a security hole, CONNECT-capable HTTP proxies commonly restrict access to the CONNECT method.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The proxy allows connections only to specific ports, such as 443 for HTTPS.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Other tunneling methods able to bypass network firewalls make use of different protocols such as DNS, MQTT, and SMS.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] As an example of network layer over network layer, Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE), a protocol running over IP (IP protocol number 47), often serves to carry IP packets, with RFC 1918 private addresses, over the Internet using delivery packets with public IP addresses.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In this case, the delivery and payload protocols are the same, but the payload addresses are incompatible with those of the delivery network.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] It is also possible to establish a connection using the data link layer.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) allows the transmission of frames between two nodes.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] A tunnel is not encrypted by default: the TCP/IP protocol chosen determines the level of security.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] SSH uses port 22 to enable data encryption of payloads being transmitted over a public network (such as the Internet) connection, thereby providing VPN functionality.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] IPsec has an end-to-end Transport Mode, but can also operate in a tunneling mode through a trusted security gateway.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] To understand a particular protocol stack imposed by tunneling, network engineers must understand both the payload and delivery protocol sets.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The throughput of a TCP‑over‑TCP connection can be degraded because the control loops in the inner and outer TCPs interfere destructively with each other.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Because TCP is designed to guarantee in‑order and complete packet delivery, the outer TCP masks the connection's health from the inner TCP.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In normal TCP operation, packet loss is detected when the receiver replies with duplicate ACKs to a packet received before the missing packet in the sequence.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In response, the sender retransmits the lost packet and halves the Congestion Window (CWND).
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In TCP‑over‑TCP, the outer TCP handles lost packets normally through retransmission and CWND reduction.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Still, since the inner TCP has not received any information indicating latency in the connection, it continues to transmit packets at the rate currently governed by its CWND.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP’s CWND is greater than the outer TCP’s, the outer TCP’s send buffer eventually fills.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] As the buffer inflates, packets experience longer and more variable queueing delays before transmission, thereby increasing the outer TCP’s measured round-trip time (RTT) and RTT variability.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] This inflates its retransmission timeout (RTO).
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Once the send buffer becomes full, the tunnel process can no longer forward inner‑TCP ACKs, so the inner TCP stops receiving acknowledgments entirely.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP is no longer receiving ACKs, its RTO expires, causing it to retransmit the oldest unacknowledged segment and double its RTO.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The inner TCP’s RTO then grows exponentially because it doubles with every timeout, and no ACKs are received to reset it.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] The result of a TCP meltdown is an outer TCP with a severely reduced CWND, an inflated RTO, and a full send buffer.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] This indicates that the inner TCP cannot write and that ACKs are not being sent in either direction.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] A *Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel* consists of an encrypted tunnel created through an SSH protocol connection.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Users may set up SSH tunnels to transfer unencrypted traffic over a network through an encrypted channel.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] It is a software-based approach to network security and the result is transparent encryption.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] For example, Microsoft Windows machines can share files using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol, a non-encrypted protocol.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] If one were to mount a Microsoft Windows file-system remotely through the Internet, someone snooping on the connection could see transferred files.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] To mount the Windows file-system securely, one can establish a SSH tunnel that routes all SMB traffic to the remote fileserver through an encrypted channel.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Even though the SMB protocol itself contains no encryption, the encrypted SSH channel through which it travels offers security.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Once an SSH connection has been established, the tunnel starts with SSH listening to a port on the remote or local host.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Any connections to it are forwarded to the specified address and port originating from the opposing (remote or local, as previously) host.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Naturally, this wrapping and unwrapping also occurs in the reverse direction of the bidirectional tunnel.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] SSH tunnels provide a means to bypass firewalls that prohibit certain Internet services – so long as a site allows outgoing connections.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] For example, an organization may prohibit a user from accessing Internet web pages (port 80) directly without passing through the organization's proxy filter (which provides the organization with a means of monitoring and controlling what the user sees through the web).
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] But users may not wish to have their web traffic monitored or blocked by the organisation's proxy filter.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] If users can connect to an external SSH server, they can create an SSH tunnel to forward a given port on their local machine to port 80 on a remote web server.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Some SSH clients support dynamic port forwarding that allows the user to create a SOCKS 4/5 proxy.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In this case users can configure their applications to use their local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] This gives more flexibility than creating an SSH tunnel to a single port as previously described.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] SOCKS can free the user from the limitations of connecting only to a predefined remote port and server.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] If an application does not support SOCKS, a proxifier can be used to redirect the application to the local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Some proxifiers, such as Proxycap, support SSH directly, thus avoiding the need for an SSH client.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In recent versions of OpenSSH it is even allowed to create layer 2 or layer 3 tunnels if both ends have enabled such tunneling capabilities.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] This creates `tun` (layer 3, default) or `tap` (layer 2) virtual interfaces on both ends of the connection.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] This allows normal network management and routing to be used, and when used on routers, the traffic for an entire subnetwork can be tunneled.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] A pair of `tap` virtual interfaces function like an Ethernet cable connecting both ends of the connection and can join kernel bridges.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] Over the years, tunneling and data encapsulation have in very rare cases been adopted for malicious reasons, in order to maliciously communicate outside of a protected network.
[src:network-overlays/tunneling-protocol] In this context, known tunnels involve protocols such as HTTP, SSH, DNS, MQTT.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] VXLAN addresses the limitations of the VLAN standard for segmenting a physical network into multiple virtual networks.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] The 12-bit VLAN identifier limits the number of virtual networks on a physical network to 4096, while in some applications, IEEE 802.1ad can be used to extend this limit, this is generally insufficient for large-scale cloud computing infrastructures with many tenants.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Also, the VXLAN standard provides for extending a virtual network across multiple geographically distributed physical networks by encapsulating layer 2 frames in UDP packets.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] This is useful for large distributed data centers.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] VXLAN is an evolution of efforts to standardize on an overlay encapsulation protocol that addresses these issues.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Compared to single-tagged IEEE 802.1Q VLANs, which provide a limited number of layer-2 VLANs (4094, using a 12-bit VLAN ID), VXLAN increases scalability up to about 16 million logical networks (using a 24-bit VNID) and allows for layer-2 adjacency across IP networks.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Multicast or unicast with head-end replication (HER) is used to flood Broadcast, unknown-unicast and multicast traffic.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] The VXLAN specification was originally created by VMware, Arista Networks and Cisco.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] VXLAN is widely, but not universally, implemented in commercial networking equipment.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Several open-source implementations of VXLAN also exist, including built-in capabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Arista, Cisco, and VMware were the originators of VXLAN and support it in various products.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] Other backers of the VXLAN technology include Adtran, Arrcus, Big Switch Networks, Broadcom, Citrix, Cumulus Networks, Dell EMC, Ericsson, Huawei, Joyent, Juniper Networks, Mellanox, MikroTik, Netgate, Netgear, Pica8, and Red Hat.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] VXLAN is officially documented by the IETF in RFC 7348.
[src:network-overlays/virtual-extensible-lan] VXLAN encapsulates a MAC frame in a UDP datagram for transport across an IP network, creating an overlay network or tunnel.
